english:
  title: A Record of Sosan and Wangyestream Hermitage
  author: Kang Hee-Maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The hermitage at Sosan and Wangyestream is the dwelling of Chae Ja-hyu, a gentleman scholar of Three Lifetimes. It had no name at first, yet who could have named it? The hermit Unsung, an old friend of Ja-hyu, gave it its name. What meaning did he draw upon? He simply followed Ja-hyu's own words in naming it—there was nothing lofty or distant in his choice.

    In the winter of the Musin year, when Ja-hyu resigned from his post as magistrate of Hamchang, he withdrew to a country estate in Eumseong, Chungcheong province. For several years he and the hermit exchanged no word. Then in the spring of the Gyeongyin year, the hermit happened upon Ja-hyu while traveling south. Moved by their long separation, they journeyed together for several days, and the hermit drew from him the nature of his contentment. "In ordinary times," the hermit observed, "you despised the ornate and cherished refinement; though your body dwelt in the city marketplace, your heart yearned for mountains and forests. Your aspirations were never those of common men. Now that you have retired from the world and dwell in leisure, surely you have found fair mountains and noble waters where supreme joy dwells and worldly cares fade away?"

    Ja-hyu smiled softly and replied: "Since I laid down my office, I have traversed countless hidden valleys and secluded hills, admired strange waters and curious stones with my own eyes. Yet nowhere had I found a place that truly answered my heart—until recently, in the Three Lifetimes village within Chungjuarea, I discovered a blessed site. To the northwest stand broken ridges; before it lies level ground, behind it rises high. The formation bends inward gently, shaped like a comb. A long stream runs along the mountainside, flowing westward for several miles until the slope meets the water in sheer cliffs. There the stream turns and winds eastward, its southern bank opening onto broad plains vast enough for ten thousand horses. To the north, clustered peaks bow in reverence—beautiful and enchanting to behold. Further east, the stream bends again like a drawn bow for two or three more miles before breaking toward the east. I loved its depth and solitude, where I might nourish my humble spirit. So I leveled the rough ground, cleared away the thorns and brambles, and built some thirty structures. One chamber I raised upon the cliff itself, a place of ease and contemplation—sufficient to shelter my body and sustain my life. Yet it still lacks a name board. Would you grace it with an inscription?"

    The hermit replied: "I have studied the ancient records. Throughout history, mountains and waters have drawn their names from their forms, and such naming is truly common. When a peak rises sharp, it is called Horse's Ear Mountain; when waters bend, they are called Bending River—all follow this pattern. So let us name your mountain Comb Mountain and your stream Waning Stream."

    Once the name was set, Ja-hyu asked the hermit to write this record. The hermit inquired: "Do you mean to dwell here always and never return to the world? Or do you merely show off your jade, hoping it will be sold?"

    Ja-hyu answered: "No. Whether I serve or do not serve is not my concern. Advance and retreat follow as circumstances dictate. My heart holds no preference—how could my body rest anywhere by mere pretense?"

    The hermit said: "Truly, you are a gentleman! When future historians compile the national records, will they place you among the chronicles of recluses, or among the ranks of worthy ministers and gentlemen? This cannot yet be known. Still, whether one holds office or not is decreed by Heaven, not obtained through seeking. You must above all examine how best to conduct yourself."

    Written by Hermit Unsung on the thirteenth day of the second month in the Gyeongyin year of the Green Dragon era, from the eastern pavilion of the old magistrate's office in Punggi.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Three Lifetimes (三生): A Buddhist concept suggesting karmic connection across multiple lives; here used as a place name and perhaps suggesting Ja-hyu''s spiritual disposition.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Comb Mountain (梳山) and Waning Stream (彎溪): The names are derived from the natural forms of the landscape—the comb-like ridge and the curved path of the water.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Hamchang: A historical administrative region in central Korea, now part of North Gyeongsang Province.'
  - key: ''
    value: The philosophical exchange between the hermit and Ja-hyu reflects Neo-Confucian ideals about withdrawal from public life while maintaining moral integrity.
